5000|$|Even {{though the}} Sui dynasty lasted only 37 years, <b>the</b> reformation <b>of</b> its <b>legal</b> {{institutions}} accomplished major results. The Kaihuang Code is regarded by historians {{as an example}} of [...] "good law" [...] and <b>the</b> origin <b>of</b> Han Chinese law. Every <b>legal</b> institution <b>of</b> <b>the</b> Tang dynasty was a direct successor to those <b>of</b> <b>the</b> Sui dynasty with the Kaihuang Code a blueprint for its laws. Later, the Song, Ming and Qing dynasties all continued to use the code, making it a fundamental part <b>of</b> <b>the</b> development <b>of</b> <b>the</b> Chinese <b>legal</b> <b>system.</b> <b>The</b> Kaihuang Code also influenced the foundation and development <b>of</b> <b>the</b> <b>legal</b> <b>systems</b> <b>of</b> other South East Asian countries including Japan, Korea and Vietnam.|$|R
